INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '397c6b86-a266-4035-85f9-261b3e5618a3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Python Unit Testing — pytest Philosophy and Why It Beats unittest$escape$,
  $escape$Python ships with `unittest`, but the ecosystem has largely converged on `pytest` for good reason. `pytest` uses plain `assert` statements instead of `self.assertEqual()` chains — when an assertion fails, pytest's introspection rewrites it into a readable diff without any extra setup. Tests are discovered automatically from any `test_*.py` file or `*_test.py` file, no class inheritance required.

The core philosophy: tests should be small, isolated, and fast. Use `pytest.fixture` to inject dependencies rather than sharing state via class attributes — fixtures are composable and scoped (`function`, `module`, `session`). Parametrize edge cases with `@pytest.mark.parametrize` instead of looping inside a test body, so each case gets its own pass/fail line in the report.

For mocking, reach for `unittest.mock.patch` (stdlib) or `pytest-mock`'s `mocker` fixture — prefer patching at the call site, not the definition. Run only changed tests with `pytest --lf` (last failed) during development. Use `pytest-cov` to enforce a coverage floor in CI.$escape$,
  $escape$import pytest
from unittest.mock import patch

def get_user(user_id: int) -> dict:
    raise NotImplementedError

@pytest.fixture
def mock_user():
    return {"id": 1, "name": "Ada"}

@pytest.mark.parametrize("user_id,expected_name", [
    (1, "Ada"),
    (2, "Grace"),
])
def test_get_user_name(user_id, expected_name, mock_user):
    mock_user["id"] = user_id
    mock_user["name"] = expected_name
    with patch("__main__.get_user", return_value=mock_user):
        result = get_user(user_id)
        assert result["name"] == expected_name$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
