INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c2e2cf30-e521-400a-b156-eb027c119bd1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Python Code Quality in 2025 — Drop flake8, black, and isort for Ruff$escape$,
  $escape$Ruff is a Rust-powered linter and formatter that replaces flake8, black, isort, pyupgrade, and flake8-bugbear in a single binary — running 10–100x faster than the Python equivalents. Configure everything via pyproject.toml.

Enable rule sets selectively: `E`/`W` for pycodestyle, `F` for Pyflakes, `I` for import sorting, `UP` for pyupgrade idioms, and `B` for bugbear. The `UP` ruleset is the highest-leverage option — it auto-rewrites legacy typing imports to modern syntax: `Optional[str]` → `str | None`, `List[int]` → `list[int]`, `Union[X, Y]` → `X | Y`. These are enforced as fixable violations, not just style suggestions.

Run `ruff check --fix .` for lint fixes and `ruff format .` for black-compatible formatting. In GitHub Actions, `--output-format=github` emits inline PR annotations automatically.

One gotcha: `--fix` skips unsafe rewrites by default — removing an unused import that has a side effect would silently break code. Pass `--unsafe-fixes` only after reviewing the diff.$escape$,
  $escape$# pyproject.toml
[tool.ruff]
target-version = "py312"
line-length = 88

[tool.ruff.lint]
select = ["E", "W", "F", "I", "UP", "B"]
ignore = ["E501"]

[tool.ruff.lint.isort]
known-first-party = ["myapp"]

# CI one-liner
# ruff check --fix --unsafe-fixes . && ruff format .$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
